Because every terminal symbol that appears in the string (t0, t1, t2, …, t16) is produced by at least one non‑terminal in the grammar, and because the grammar contains numerous binary rules that can combine those producing non‑terminals in arbitrarily nested ways (there are many self‑recursions such as NT16 → NT16 NT48, NT33 → NT33 NT2, etc.), each of the two symbols on the right‑hand side of the start rule S → NT31 NT3 can derive strings of any desired length and of unrestricted terminal order.  Consequently, the 35‑token sequence given can be split between NT31 and NT3 in some way, and the internal recursion available under those symbols can generate exactly the required subsequences of terminals.  Hence the whole string is derivable from S.  

Yes
